To create a TikZ LaTeX diagram representing a Stokes arrow between a positive and a negative sector, we can follow these steps:

1. Define the sectors.
2. Find the midpoints of the sectors.
3. Draw a path connecting the midpoints, going around at least one singular direction.
4. Indicate the path on the left-hand side using the Legendre transform.

Here is the TikZ LaTeX code for the diagram:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]

% Define the sectors
\draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1); % Positive sector
\draw[thick] (-1,-1) rectangle (1,1); % Negative sector

% Midpoints of the sectors
\coordinate (mid_pos) at (0,0);
\coordinate (mid_neg) at (0,0);

% Draw the path connecting the midpoints
\draw[->, thick, red] (mid_pos) -- node[midway, above] {Path} ++(0.5,0.5) arc[start angle=-90, end angle=90, radius=0.5];

% Left-hand side path indication
\node[left, text width=3cm, align=center] at (0,-2) {Legendre transform};
\draw[dashed, ->, blue] (0,-1) -- node[midway, below] {Path} ++(-1,-1);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce a diagram with a positive sector and a negative sector, connected by a red path that goes around at least one singular direction. The path on the left-hand side is indicated using a dashed blue line and labeled as "Path" with the Legendre transform noted above it. Adjust the coordinates and angles as needed to better fit your specific requirements.

